The mixture left seven dead and five more are in a critical condition. Courtesy #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - The community of Masiphumelele township in Cape Town is still in shock after several people died after consuming a home-brewed beer believed to contain methanol. The mixture left seven dead and five more are in a critical condition. Richard Chinembiri says he saw his life flash before his eyes after he fell violently ill. Chinembiri’s brother, Tapera, is among the dead. The deceased’s wife, Senai Rungano, who’s expecting her third child, says her late husband was the family’s breadwinner. “Now we are trying to raise money for his body to go back to Zimbabwe but still it is difficult,” she said. READ: Hospitals hit by alcohol-related incidents It’s believed the men consumed the home brew at a house party just a day before the lifting of the alcohol ban. Police are still searching for the suspect who sold the home brew. READ: Liquor forum calls on bottle stores to act responsibly The incident has left many in the community more aware of what they consume and the importance of finding out about the contents of any mixtures they drink. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday. Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.